 of the philosophies of Socrates, Plato, Hegel, Marx, Nietzsche, and Adorno play a central role in many of these essays. Geuss also ranges over such topics as the concepts of intelligibility, authority, democracy, and criticism; the role of lying in politics; architecture; the place of theology in ethics; tragedy and comedy; and the struggle between realism and our search for meaning.Characterized by Geuss's wide-ranging interests in literature, philosophy, and history, and by his political commitment and trenchant style, A World without Why raises fundamental questions about the viability not just of specific ethical concepts and theses, but of our most basic assumptions about what ethics could and must be.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aPhilosophyxEssays. 0aPhilosophyxHistory and SurveysxGeneral. 0aPhilosophyxHistory and SurveysxModern. 0aPhilosophyxHistory. 0aPhilosophy, Moderny21st century. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Essays.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066592540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978140084848540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400848485423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400848485.jpg  a978-3-11-066592-5  Princeton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK